		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13125'>NoMercy_3</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">ok I reread it.  I&#39;ll finally review.  <br />
<br />
problem 1:  too many lackluster sets.<br />
Now that i&#39;ve been playing lotr online I REALLY REALLY notice this more than before.  being forced to rebuild my collection with limited amounts of $$$ really focus on this.  How many boosters of mom, bohd, eof do you think i&#39;ve bought?  0.  How many of elflords?  like 10, because some of the cards in it are good in fellowship block (and far less in standard).  <br />
<br />
One thing I disagree with is initiative.  Now, I agree that this is an idea that shouldn&#39;t have hit the DRAWING BOARD, let alone get off it.  but even so, it ALMOST came out as a well desinged mechanic.  Designing shadow strategies around initiative was a horrible idea.  Desiging SOME shadow cards which get a bonus with initiative was good though.  Ulaire Toldea, for example.  Still a good minion, gets a bonus when you have initiative.  Bad ideas were the sauron trackers, who suck when you don&#39;t have it and are a whole strategy.  Good ideas were any fellowship initiative cards.  Almost all of these use initiative as some type of requirement, including a built in limit to the cards.  Good idea!  Making shadow cards that take initiative away, making those cards useles.. bad idea!<br />
<br />
Problem 2: Horrible Marketing<br />
The marketing SUCKS at attracting new players, but is excellent at keeping &#39;non serious&#39; players who will eat up the crap decipher shoves their way.  countdown to the king is an example of this, a way for decipher to take our money and pretend to give us something of value.  so are the tengwar cards.  Deciphers idea of marketing isn&#39;t to attract new players, it&#39;s to take more of the current players money IMMEDIATELY.  instead of spending money to make money, they want to spend $0 to make money.  Hey, it&#39;s risk free, right?  <br />
<br />
Problem 3: Tournement structure.<br />
ok, say it with me.  The new system SUCKS.  Spending $$$ for tournements with little to no prize support is awful!  Do you know why I got hooked on card games ?  Cause I could go to a star wars tournement and win more cards!  This made me play the game more, and the more I played, the more I bought.  they spent $$, and made $$ cause of it.  <br />
lotronline is doing this same idea.  It costs $5 to enter a tournement of 8 players.  Bad Idea?  sounds like it, until you realize they give out 5 packs to 1st, 4 to 2nd, and so on, following a 5-4-3-2-1-1-1-1 system.  Take top 4 and get your money back.  miss top 4 and lose only a tiny bit.  They give out more product than you pay for.  <br />
<br />
Booster draft only costs $2 plus pack fee to enter (with draft packs being only slightly more than a booster), and follow a 5-4-3-2-0 support I think.  Even better !<br />
<br />
I disagree with the DGMA comments.  I&#39;ve found DGMA tournments to be run EXCELLENTLY.  This is of course, due to great judges like Enrique Huerta and Gabe Alonso.  On the flip side, i&#39;ve found DPC&#39;s to really vary.  This is to be expected from something like the DPC, which isn&#39;t being run by a company and just has &#39;whoevers there&#39; to run the things.  If Decipher were to contract out the tournement system to decktech and the DPC, some massive changes would also have to be made to the DPC.  There is far too much variance, a &#39;DPC authority&#39; of some type would need to be implemented, or DPCs could only be run by &#39;approved&#39; people.  Unfortunately, this opens up a whole bag of worms where less DPCs will happen because the system is more strict to allow for one to happen.  Thems the breaks.<br />
<br />
Of course, we&#39;ll have to see what happens with decipher funny money possibly being next years prizes.  Once upon a time I might have flow to 3-4 cons a year (if i could afford it) to play cards with people from around the world.  Now I fly to that many cause of the chance of cash.  If funny money is the prize to be had, I&#39;m probably only going to ONE con/tournement that requires flying.<br />
<br />
Final Problem:<br />
I can&#39;t comment on this too much.  I don&#39;t know how the inside of decipher runs, how much power the various people have, how lax they are, whatever.  <br />
I will say that decipher really seems to try to feel like a &#39;family&#39; atmosphere.  A small time company that never wants to fire anybody.  That&#39;s the wrong feel for a game like lotr.  This game needed a company that was willing to sack those who didn&#39;t work.  If I was running a games company, and I saw sets like bohd and eof come out in a ROW, I&#39;d sack the entire team that made those (unless they&#39;d shown me before that they shouldn&#39;t be sacked...  even then, a big shakeup of some sort would be in order).<br />
<br />
I also gotta add in that I don&#39;t think I agree with the &#39;asking for certain people to be fired&#39; bits.  Including such things in an article immediately gives it the impression of a rant, and also lowers it&#39;s credibility to anyone who is a fan of decipher, and espescially decipher itself.  It might have been better to write the article (sans names) then drop the names on the buzzboard :P<br />
<br />
So there you have it.  My review (almost an article) of your article.  eh?<br />
