		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14999'>TheTrooper</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">I agree with a lot of what you said, Neal.  The player base really is dying off.  In the last few months I&#39;ve been to more tournaments that never happened because only 5 people (the same 5, every time) showed up than actual tournaments that got sanctioned and happened.  People rarely bring trade binders anymore because there&#39;s simply no one to trade with.  I can&#39;t fathom why this game isn&#39;t selling like hotcakes, or more pointedly, like LotR merchandise.  Heck, I couldn&#39;t even interest my old SWCCG buddies in the FREE open online beta!  Although I disagree with your statements about how bad the sets have been lately.  No, they&#39;ve never been as good as FotR was.  But I think at least part of the blame lies with New Line Cinema.  In FotR, so many images were released before the movie came out that Decipher could include pretty much anything but the Balrog and the Twilight Nazgul.  As a result, almost ALL of the factions in the film got representation in the base set.  Only Twilight Nazgul and Isengard Orcs were made to wait, and hey, you&#39;ve gotta save something for the expansions.  But in Tower Block, New Line was so miserly with the images that tons of interesting things had to wait for the expansions, where they were only afforded a cursory glance.  As a result, everything suffered.  The strategies introduced in the base set got little to no additional support: Uruk Trackers, Battleground Uruks, and Uruk Site Control never got anything more; RBRs, Easterlings, and Naith Elves had to wait until EoF for a mere pittance of cards.  The strategies introduced in the expansions suffered: Smeagol/Gollum, Warg-riders, Knights, Sauron Orcs, Ents (yes Ents!) and Besiegers lacked the card pool to give them significant depth.  Any two decks using them were much the same and almost always had holes that were never plugged up.  The only culture that DIDN&#39;T suffer like this was Rohan and look how well it did for itself.  Which is the main problem with Decipher&#39;s design style.  Cultural distinction is very nice on paper, but the fact is that LotR has gameplay elements that win games and gameplay elements that may be fun but won&#39;t win games, and all too often Decipher&#39;s decisions of which culture gets what leaves some cultures with too much and others with too little.  This leaves players with the choice of playing decks that are boring but will win, or decks that are fun but won&#39;t, which is a losing choice no matter which way you go.  <font size=1>(+3 tp)</font><BR>
